<TEXT>
a victim of last weeks bridge collapse over 
the great miami river was identified thursday but efforts to 
recover other bodies were hampered by inadequate equipment and 
strong river currents officials said 
hamilton county sheriff simon leis jr identified the victim as 
helen c zorn 52 of nearby green township her decomposed body 
was recovered tuesday from surfaced debris leis said 
still missing was her daughter terry siemon 27 who was 
believed to have been with mrs zorn as the two were driving over 
the bridge when it collapsed last friday afternoon said sheriffs 
spokesman frank weikel 
no other bodies or either of two submerged vehicles believed to 
have fallen from the bridge were recovered thursday said lt 
chris robertson one of five police divers on the search team 
in another development a sheriffs deputy directing traffic at 
the bridge site died at a cincinnati hospital after suffering a 
heart attack late thursday afternoon he was identified as sgt 
robert mondary 51 a 21year veteran 
robertson said police divers were frustrated by strong 
underwater currents and little or no visibility underwater 
reducing divers to feeling in the darkness for objects 
were fighting current its like trying to hang onto the back 
of a boat robertson told reporters 
a cranes grappling hook broke off and was lost underwater in 
the murky river thursday afternoon prompting officials to call off 
the rest of the days recovery efforts at the site 12 miles west of 
cincinnati 
police are unsure how many people were swept into the river but 
based on eyewitness reports police believe two vehicles and as 
many as five people fell in when a 100foot section of the bridge 
collapsed 
the onelane temporary bridge opened to traffic in december 
while workmen built a nearby replacement for a 94yearold bridge 
collapsed during rush hour while taking a pounding from large 
debris in a strong current swelled by heavy rains 
</TEXT>
