<TEXT>
the daily shapeup of longshoremen looking 
for jobs so vividly portrayed in the film on the waterfront is 
going the way of silent movies but in a talky way 
a new phonein system is taking its place 
its the end of an era for that type of hiring of 
longshoremen something thats been in existence for 36 years 
said jerome j klied deputy director of the waterfront commission 
of new york harbor as the commission announced the change thursday 
on the waterfront which won four academy awards in 1954 
depicted corruption part of which was the daily socalled shapeup 
on the piers once the men gathered for work the jobs in 
reellife and reallife were passed out on the basis of kickbacks 
and friendships among other corruptions 
it was a very degrading form of employment klied said 
in 1953 the waterfront commission was created to end that 
freewheeling system 
now the workers get their assignments by telephone the day 
before they work only unemployed longshoremen show up each day in 
one of three employment centers hoping to get the 50 slots left 
vacant by absentees 
under the system that goes into effect tuesday employers will 
factor in the vacancies and call up the unemployed the day before 
an assignment 
</TEXT>
