the chief of the kgb said thursday that the 
newly elected soviet legislature should have have full authority 
over his agency and use us congressional oversight as its model 
the new york times reported 
vladimir a kryuchkov in his first interview with western 
reporters said the supreme soviet would probably create a 
commission similar to the congressional committees charged with 
overseeing intelligence activities in the united states the times 
reported in its friday editions 
we are decidedly in favor of this he said and as far as 
the creation of a commission is concerned i think well borrow 
some of the experience of the americans 
included in the legislatures powers would be the authority to 
approve the appointment of the kgb chairman kryuchkov said 
human rights activists have said the kgb should be accountable 
to the new legislature in order to protect rights and curb police 
powers 
kryuchkov who was appointed last october spoke with reporters 
a day after a member of the new congress yuri p vlasov charged 
that the kgb exercises allembracing control over society over 
each individual 
the frankness of the accusation shocked other legislators and 
millions listening on radio and television broadcasts 
the kgb is technically overseen by the council of ministers the 
administrative branch of government but in practice it has been 
virtually independent 
