<TEXT>
if youre looking to buy a new home the decline in interest 
rates over the past few weeks could open a few doors 
economists say an improved inflation outlook and stronger dollar 
have helped reverse a stubborn upward trend in rates that began two 
years ago and has sent the oncevibrant housing industry into a 
slump 
many people out there who wouldnt be able to buy a home can 
now qualify at the lower rates richard w peach deputy chief 
economist of the mortgage bankers association of america said 
thursday 
at the same time rates on some certificates of deposit have 
fallen while changes in other types of consumer interest charges 
such as bank auto loans and credit cards have been mixed 
many experts predict interest rates will continue easing the 
rest of the year as the us economy slows and as foreigners 
attracted by a firm dollar pump money into us financial 
investments some predict fixedrate mortgages could drop to 10 
percent before the end of the year 
fixedrate loans have dropped most steeply over the last two 
months dropping below 11 percent in tandem with declining 
longterm rates in the credit markets 
but adjustable rate mortages which are tied to an index of 
oneyear treasury notes have shown only a slight drop because 
shortterm rates remain comparably high that stems from the 
federal reserves decision to keep a tigher rein on credit to fight 
inflation 
the average rate on the first year of an arm was 918 percent 
the last week in may down from 928 percent the previous week 
according to the latest bank survey of the federal home loan 
mortgage corp the rate averaged 940 percent in april 
freddie mac said the average rate on fixed 30year mortgages 
fell to a fivemonth low of 105 percent the last week in may down 
from 1069 percent the week before just two months ago that same 
loan averaged 1122 percent a nearly fouryear high and in may 
1988 it averaged 1046 percent it said 
the decline of nearly threequarters of a percentage point in 
30year fixedrate mortgages over the past two months could mean 
significant savings in comparing monthly mortgage payments 
homebuyers for example who got a 100000 conventional loan at 
the 1122 percent rate are paying 972 a month in interest and 
principal those who took out a mortgage last week at 105 percent 
pay 915 or 684 less a year for a 6 percent difference 
that could mean the difference between qualifying for a mortgage 
and having to put homebuying plans on hold for some the rule of 
thumb is that monthly mortgage payments not exceed 25 percent of 
net household income 
for every half percentage point increase or decrease 
another half a million people get in the housing market or out of 
the housing market said ronnie j wynn president of montgomery 
alabased colonial mortgage co one of the nations largest 
mortgage companies 
wynn said business is brisker these days as people rush to 
exploit the break in rates loan applications are running about 20 
percent higher than a year ago compared with a 10 percent drop in 
applications during april he said 
stephen ashley president of the rochester nybased mortgage 
banker sibley corp said his business was slower than last year 
but he expects it to pick up this summer 
i think that the drop in rates has been positive in terms of 
bringing a greater number of homebuyers into the market but i 
dont want to represent it as being a land rush he said 
while fixedrate mortgages have come down significantly other 
consumer interest charges havent 
a 48month bank loan for a new car averages 1256 percent up 
from 1254 percent a month ago and 1173 percent at the beginning 
of the year according to the north palm beach fla publication 
bank rate monitor 
bank credit cards average 1813 percent up from 1809 percent a 
month ago and 1803 percent earlier this year bank rate monitor 
reported 
for savers rate changes have been mixed the yield on a 
oneyear certificate of deposit has an average yield of 928 
percent down from 951 percent a month ago according to the 
publication 
money market accounts yielded an average 662 percent in the 
week ended wednesday unchanged from the previous month it said 
</TEXT>
