the nuclear regulatory commission citing a 
long lag in promised improvements at a florida nuclear plant said 
it might consider closing the twinreactor station later this year 
the commission raised the possibility of such an extraordinary 
step after announcing thursday that the no 3 and 4 units at the 
turkey point nuclear station near florida city fla would be 
kept on its watch list of troubled plants 
as a result of its regular sixmonth review of all 110 licensed 
us nuclear power plants the commission took four reactors off 
the watch list added two others and expressed deep concern that 
turkey point has been on the list for three years 
turkey point is the only plant in the nation to appear on the 
nrcs category 2 watch list each time since the list was 
started in 1986 plants in this category are allowed to continue 
running but only with increased nrc supervision 
the commission said thursday it was adding a third resident 
inspector at turkey point to beef up oversight 
regulators also said they were keeping the tennessee valley 
authoritys browns ferry 1 2 and 3 reactors on their category 
3 watch list which is reserved for plants that are shut down and 
cannot restart without special nrc approval 
the pilgrim plant near plymouth mass and the peach bottom 
units 2 and 3 near lancaster pa were moved up to category 2 to 
reflect the fact that they have been allowed to restart both will 
continue to receive special nrc monitoring until they demonstrate a 
sustained improvement in operations the commission said 
the regulators also announced that two nuclear reactors owned by 
virginia power co had been added to the watch list in part 
because of increased violations of nrc rules just last month the 
utility was fined 500000 the sixth largest fine since the 
commission was created in 1975 for violating safety regulations 
the surry no 1 and 2 reactors are situated near newport news va 
the watch list includes four other operating reactors calvert 
cliffs no 1 and 2 of annapolis md and nine mile point no 1 
and 2 of oswego ny 
victor stello the commissions chief of operations told a 
commission meeting were very disappointed that the turkey 
point reactors has remained on the problem list for three years 
without showing a clear improvement trend 
stello said without explicitly suggesting that turkey point be 
forced to close that more drastic nrc action might be required 
unless the plants owner florida power amp light co made faster 
progress in solving the problems 
three of the five commissioners made similar remarks 
i dont know how long the commission can continue to monitor 
turkey point with increased resources said lando w zech jr 
the commission chairman 
i think the florida power amp light organization should 
recognize that the commissions patience is wearing very thin he 
said adding turkey point has not shown us much 
kenneth carr a commission member said in a tone of incredulity 
that he found it interesting that while turkey point had failed 
to get well after three years of intensified nrc monitoring 
most nuclear plants that had been forced to shut down because of 
operating problems had managed to recover in two years 
we might have done them a favor by forcing turkey point to 
close he added 
spokesmen at florida power amp light did not return a reporters 
telephone call 
earlier this week the company said it had achieved vast 
improvements at turkey point over the past year it was 
responding to a report by an antinuclear group public citizen 
that ranked turkey point no 3 as the worstrun nuclear plant in 
the country it rated the turkey point no 4 unit as 10th worst 
the four reactors that were removed from the nrc watch list 
thursday are sequoyah no 1 and 2 of chattanooga tenn fermi2 
of newport mich and fort calhoun of omaha neb 
