<TEXT>
eastern airlines will pay 31 million to 
several of its benefit plans to settle a case in which the 
government alleged the carrier illegally tapped employee funds to 
pay corporate expenses 
the bankrupt airline could face up to another 55 million in 
bills to cover the costs of audits it agreed to conduct for the 
past three years as well as through 1994 
eastern still operating a skeleton schedule three months into a 
strike by its machinists union entered into a consent agreement 
with the labor department on thursday without admitting or denying 
it violated its duties under federal pension laws 
the cashpoor airline issued a statement saying the alleged 
technical violations were discovered after a 1987 internal audit 
and that it voluntarily brought them to the attention of the labor 
department 
because eastern has filed for court protection from creditors 
under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law the settlement will 
have to be approved by a bankruptcy court in new york 
the labor department complaint alleged that beginning in 1977 
eastern violated its trust responsibilities through an informal 
arrangement in which it used insurance commissions earned by its 
welfare plans to offset actuarial expenses of the company it also 
alleged that eastern paid its remaining corporate actuarial 
expenses from assets of its pension plans 
specifically the complaint said eastern violated federal 
pension laws by 
using 21 million in commissions generated by insurance 
policies of the welfare plans to offset what it owed to a company 
known as mercermeidingerhansen inc for corporate and 
pensionrelated work the welfare plans funded entirely with 
employee contributions provide travel and longterm disability 
insurance to eastern workers 
causing definedbenefit plans to pay for actuarial services 
related to easterns corporate affairs including 250000 for work 
unrelated to the benefit plans 
receiving excessive fees for administrating the travel accident 
plan from 1975 to 1987 
failing to file reports required by the government for the 
travel accident plan 
under terms of the order eastern must pay into escrow accounts 
675285 for the disability plan and 18 million for the travel 
accident plan also the company must pay another 591713 to seven 
of its 11 defined benefits plans 
eastern also agreed to pay up to 800000 a year for annual 
audits between now and 1994 and up to another 15 million for 
audits covering the past three years 
results of those audits are to be included in reports eastern 
must file for the next five years demonstrating its compliance with 
the pension laws the agreement requires eastern to hire a third 
party acceptable to the labor department to prepare the reports 
eastern also was permanently barred from using assets of 
employee benefit plans to pay for corporate expenses 
mercermeidinger which was not a party to the case agreed in a 
side letter to establish a compliance unit responsible for 
implementing a program to assure that it does not allow violations 
of the pension laws the complaint did not cite the company but 
alleged eastern had an informal arrangement with mercermeidinger 
that led to the alleged violations 
 
</TEXT>
