<TEXT>
the government has approved a genetically 
engineered drug that can help reduce anemia in patients suffering 
from kidney failure and may also benefit cancer and aids patients 
the drug approved by the food and drug administration thursday 
is a copy of a natural human protein erythropoietin which 
stimulates the body to produce red blood cells 
lack of those cells which carry energygiving oxygen around the 
body is known as anemia and since the kidneys produce 
erythropoietin patients with kidney failure often develop anemia 
food and drug commissioner frank young said that in addition to 
about 95000 kidney patients who should benefit from the new drug 
it also may be useful to chronically anemic patients suffering from 
other diseases such as cancer and aids 
