<TEXT>
federal health officials say an aids education 
program targeting intravenous drug users in sacramento calif has 
reduced practices that increase the risk of transmitting the aids 
virus 
the centers for disease control reported thursday that 23 
percent of the intravenous drug users interviewed in sacramento in 
1986 said they did not share needles or usually or always 
sterilized their paraphernalia 
the report said the figure climbed to 41 percent in 1988 after 
the education prevention and testing program was begun 
drug users testing negative for the human immunodeficiency virus 
hiv that causes aids were encouraged and paid to return after 
four months for followup testing the study said 24 percent did so 
and all continued to test negative of those returning 57 percent 
reported using safer shooting techniques 
aids or acquired immune deficiency syndrome destroys the 
bodys defenses against disease leaving a person prey to 
lifethreatening infections and certain cancers 
the virus that causes the asyet incurable disease is passed 
mainly through sexual contact shared hypodermic needles 
contaminated blood and blood products and from infected mothers to 
offspring 
the cdc report described the gains in the sacramento program as 
modest but said such programs are important in reducing the 
risk of transmitting the aids virus 
worcester mass has begun a similar program in jails where 
needleusers are concentrated 
the cdc said the sacramento program recruited drug users from 
drug treatment programs jails public hospitals and a county 
testing and counseling site the city of 330000 has an estimated 
8000 intravenous drug users 
it often takes years from the time of exposure to the virus 
until diagnosis of the disease so the study measured only 
behavior not the number of aids cases among participants 
in worcester the cdc said surveys showed that 70 percent of 
the jail inmates who used intravenous drugs had never been in a 
rehabilitation program seventyseven percent of those describing 
themselves as recent needle users said they had shared needles 
the study there showed that more than half of the recent needle 
users at treatment clinics and rehabilitation programs had been in 
jail recently and that among recent needle users recruited in jail 
for the study 83 percent had been in jail before 
the worcester program illustrates the potential impact of hiv 
prevention programs on intravenous drug users in correctional 
institutions the cdc report said 
it said the highest instances of positive testing for the aids 
antibody among needle users are in new york city and puerto rico 
between 45 percent and 60 percent 
the report said the high rate indicates the potential for rapid 
transmission of the virus to uninfected needle users 
the report said results similar to those achieved in sacramento 
may be more difficult to achieve in larger cities with larger 
numbers of drug users 
</TEXT>
