<DOCNO> AP890602-0078 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
clr james a caribbeanborn political 
historian marxist philosopher novelist political activist and 
cricket writer has died at his home above a bookshop in south 
londons largely black brixton district colleagues said he was 88 
the london newspaper the independent hailed james in an obituary 
today as probably the most versatile and accomplished 
afroamerican intellectual of the 20th century 
writer and television producer tariq ali said james died 
wednesday no cause of death was stated and obituary notices made 
no mention of any family members 
frail with white hair lean features and a quavering voice 
james exercised a considerable influence over independence 
movements in africa and the caribbean after world war ii 
his support for marxist revolution and sharp criticism of 
opponents contrasted with his softspoken charm eloquence and 
gentle manner 
cyril lionel robert james was born at tunapuna near port of 
spain trinidad in 1901 and like his father became a teacher 
educated at queens royal college one of the exbritish 
colonys top schools he had an encyclopedic knowledge of english 
literature and history and a command of latin and ancient greek 
he left trinidad in 1932 at the urging of fellow trinidadian 
learie constantine later lord constantine who was then a 
professional cricketer and became a political leader in britain 
james went to stay with constantine at nelson in northwest 
england and published his first book life of captain cipriani 
soon after his arrival 
the book about a trinidadian politician agitating on behalf of 
working class people there was financed by constantine 
with the support of british cricket writer neville cardus james 
began to write about the game for the northern england newspaper 
the manchester guardian he later wrote books about the game which 
had been a passion with him since boyhood days 
moving to london later in the 1930s he became a marxist and 
involved himself in leftwing political causes of the time 
his close colleague at that time was fellow trinidadian george 
padmore a former member of the 3rd communist international or 
comintern founded in moscow 
padmore had been head of the comintern department responsible 
for what it called negro propaganda but in 1935 he broke with 
soviet leader joseph stalin and came to london where he produced a 
journal dedicated to african emancipation that james edited 
james bestknown book the black jacobins was published in 
1938 with the rise of fascism and the 1936 italian invasion of 
ethiopia in mind it told of black revolt in haiti against french 
rule during the french revolution at the end of the 18th century 
in a shift of political views james came to reject stalins 
brand of communism siding instead with stalins exiled rival leon 
trotsky james and trotsky met in 1939 in mexico trotsky was 
assassinated there the following year at what is thought to have 
been stalins instigation 
soon after publication of the black jacobins which won wide 
acclaim james went to the united states having established a 
close relationship in london with the black american singer and 
political activist paul robeson he and robeson worked together on 
african and negro issues 
james spent 15 years in america addressing books and articles 
on political issues to small black marxist and labor groups 
he was expelled from the united states in 1953 during the 
anticommunist campaign headed by the late sen joseph mccarthy and 
again became involved in the african independence movement 
james returned to trinidad in 1958 at the invitation of dr eric 
williams the chief minister to edit his partys newspaper and 
later became secretary of the west indies federal labor party 
but he differed with williams left trinidad and in the 1960s 
and 1970s was permitted back into the united states for a series of 
college lecture tours 
he later returned to live in britain where a group of admirers 
mostly young and black gathered around him heralding him as a 
trotskyite sage his writing meanwhile inspired numerous young 
intellectuals in the caribbean 
funeral arrangements were incomplete 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

