<TEXT>
some trucks are doing double duty of 
the most distasteful kind hauling food to market in the east and 
returning to the midwest filled with garbage for landfills a 
newspaper reported 
food truckers at plazas on interstate 80 in pennsylvania tell of 
going to midwest landfills with 20 or more tons of baled garbage on 
their return runs the centre daily times reported 
in recent weeks a reporter from the newspaper saw many 
tractortrailers and refrigerator trucks either carrying or being 
loaded with municipal solid waste at a transfer station in 
pennsylvania and being unloaded at a large ohio landfill 
the fact that garbage is moving in dry vans and refrigerator 
trucks that sometimes also carry food is something thats becoming 
increasingly apparent said dave pointon of the national solid 
wastes management association as an association we feel it is 
unhealthy unaesthetic and unappealing but right now theres 
nothing on the books to prohibit it 
the us department of agriculture prohibits the hauling of meat 
and poultry products in any vehicle that has carried inedible 
cargo and the us food and drug administration requires 
interstate carriers of all other food products to provide clean and 
sanitary vehicles 
but truck drivers said it was easy to get around those 
regulations and officials said it was difficult to catch violators 
the newspaper reported 
one truck from michigan said the use of deodorizers and coffee 
grounds combined with a quick sweep can fool federal authorities 
and workers on food loading docks the newspaper reported sunday 
the story was reprinted today in the philadelphia inquirer 
it boggles the imagination manfred kroger professor of 
food science at pennsylvania state university told the daily times 
last week the implications of food contamination are tremendous 
its like shipping milk to alaska and bringing back oil in the same 
truck 
trucking association officials said they know nothing of the 
practice but drivers said dispatchers have been routinely steering 
them to solidwaste transfer stations in philadelphia allentown 
and bloomsburg and jersey city nj for the last year or two 
the executive director of the alexandria vabased interstate 
truckload carriers conference terry turner said last week that he 
knew nothing about the hauling of food and garbage in the same 
trucks but he did say trucking companies are rushing to get cargo 
to avoid returning empty from the east 
the east coast consumes so much more than it produces that 
truckers trying to come out of there either cut rates run empty 
or haul what they can haul a truck either makes money or it 
doesnt stay on the road he said 
according to the newspaper truckers and solidwaste industry 
representatives say backhauling garbage is burgeoning because of a 
lack of government and other regulations a dwindling number of 
garbage disposal sites in the east and economic competition in the 
trucking industry 
a food industry spokesmen was astounded when he heard of the 
practice 
it would be the worst imaginable publicity for our products to 
be in any way associated with garbage dumps or landfills said 
dennis madsen of the washingtonbased national american wholesale 
grocers association the trend in our industry is to get more 
backhauls but certainly not garbage im sure our membership 
would think this abhorrent 
