<TEXT>
the greek orthodox church of cyprus lost 
spiritual treasures when four sixthcentury byzantine mosaics were 
removed from a church in northern cyprus a church abbot testified 
the mosaics are at the center of a legal battle pitting the 
church and the greek cypriot government against indianapolis art 
dealer peg goldberg who purchased them for 11 million last 
summer 
the church claims the early christian mosaics were ripped from 
the walls of the church and smuggled out of the troubled 
mediterranean island nation 
the church wants the mosaics back because they are our 
spiritual treasures abbot paul of macheras testified in us 
district court thursday the trial resumed today 
they were once put up on the wall and they were sanctified 
through the prayers and holy literature they are a part of our 
sacred life 
the bearded abbot wearing a flowing black headdress and robe 
and carrying a black staff topped with gold said the archbishop 
had never allowed the mosaics to be removed from the church of 
panagia kanakaria 
the church is in an area controlled by a turkish breakaway state 
recognized by no countries other than turkey most greek cypriots 
have left the area since it came under turkish control in 1974 
athanasis papageorghiou acting director of cypriot antiquities 
said the removal of the mosaics was part of a widespread pattern of 
looting in churches in northern cyprus 
judge james e noland accepted the pretrial deposition of 
ronald faulk a los angeles attorney who helped arrange the 
purchase of the mosaics in switzerland 
faulks deposition said aydin dikmen a turkish national living 
in germany agreed to sell the mosaics for 350000 
dikmen was paid 350000 and faulk received 80000 robert 
fitzgerald an indianapolis art dealer who brought goldberg into 
the deal got the remaining 650000 said faulk who represents 
fitzgerald 
fitzgerald testified today that goldberg obtained a bank loan of 
12 million to buy the mosaics and he was paid 300000 for his 
role in the deal in addition he will receive almost a quarter of 
the profits if goldberg is allowed to sell the mosaics he said 
goldbergs bill of sale listed a purchase price of 1080000 
according to court records 
the mosaics pieced together by an unknown artist about 525 
ad are representations of christ as a boy the apostles james 
and matthew and an archangel 
they are among only a handful of byzantine icons surviving from 
the first centuries of christianity experts say 
goldberg has offered to sell the mosaics for 20 million to the 
j paul getty museum in malibu calif 
</TEXT>
