<TEXT>
paul casella wants his mtv only with 
poetry 
with the production of his first poetry television videotape 
casella hopes to popularize poetry through ptv 
its a pretty blatant ripoff of music television which is so 
common now its an adjective unto itself casella said but 
poetry can be so cool it just doesnt get out anywhere 
casella 24 attending the writers workshop at the university of 
iowa is hoping that will change his 50minute ptv video which he 
spent four months putting together is a collection of 35 poems by 
15 other members of the graduate writers workshop 
as poetry is read words designs and images swirl onto the 
screen some poems are illustrated by videotape some show nothing 
but a closeup of the poet with different lighting projected in the 
background 
some of the poets puff on cigarettes others use profanity one 
reads in spanish 
casella who has an interest in cinematography designed most of 
the background graphics and lighting occasionally collaborating 
with the authors he said it only cost 162 to make the tape some 
of which was paid for by a grant 
mtv works because the music and the video complement each 
other you can sit back and watch he said here my biggest 
conflict is that its so easy to make an image look good its so 
easy to make it look interesting but you have to pay attention 
too i dont want to take away from the poems 
casellas ptv video went on sale this week for 10 at the 
prairie lights bookstore in iowa city it is scheduled for three 
airings this month on the universitys campus channel which can be 
seen in iowa city solon cedar rapids and north liberty 
casella has sent copies of the video to dartmouth cornell and 
colgate universities the university of chicago the university of 
californiasanta barbara and on michigan public television with 
hopes that they will air it 
the ptv idea was spawned in 1987 when casella then a student at 
dartmouth college won third place at the poetry film festival in 
san francisco with a 25minute blackandwhite video of readings 
from 16 companions 
for ptvs theme casella borrowed a quote from author kurt 
vonnegut who once taught at the iowa writers workshop were in 
great trouble now that television can tell stories better than we 
can 
diana beeson campus channel program director said ptv is one 
of the most original concepts in programming ive seen in a long 
long time 
poetry is a very intimate medium and so is television this is 
one of the things that makes ptv so engaging she said 
casella sent a copy to the arts and entertainment network 
brooke bailey johnson vice president of programming and 
production wrote back that ptv was an interesting and 
challenging concept but the networks schedule was set for 
198990 
casella who is already planning a sequel said he is reluctant 
to send the videotape to mtv because theyd edit the hell out of 
it 
