<DOCNO> AP890602-0171 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a transplant surgeon said friday hes devised a 
way to maintain kidneys in trauma victims for several hours after 
their hearts stop a plan that could ease the organ shortage but 
one thats sure to spark controversy 
its clearly something we have to start looking at as a 
source because there is no other solution said david anaise 
clinical associate professor at the state university of new york at 
stony brook 
anaise proposes tapping into the pool of patients who die in 
accidents but are not sustained by respirators as are some 
braindead victims currently the sole source for transplant 
organs by the time relatives of unsustained trauma victims are 
notified it usually is too late for organ donation 
organs quickly deteriorate and thus become useless for 
transplantation unless they are chilled and flushed with 
preservatives 
anaise said trauma victims kidneys could be maintained in their 
bodies for up to five hours if solutions were pumped into the 
organs via a catheter 
with nearly 15000 people awaiting kidney transplants in the 
united states the need for more organs is acute according to 
anaise he estimates the number of kidney donors could double if 
kidneys automatically were maintained in trauma victims while 
family consent was being sought 
last year kidneys were offered from the families of 3867 
victims nationwide according to the united network for organ 
sharing the kidneys of 966 percent of them or 3737 actually 
were transplanted 
the university of wisconsins dr folkert belzer developer of a 
new solution that has improved organ preservation said he doubts 
many kidneys would be obtained from trauma victims whose families 
cannot be reached immediately 
anaises plan is technically feasible belzer said since 
similar methods were used to a limited extent during the 1970s the 
results then were not encouraging 
some doctors worry about the ethical and legal ramifications of 
maintaining kidneys for transplantation without family consent 
its certainly not as invasive as going ahead and removing the 
organs said dr j wesley alexander president of the american 
society of transplant surgeons but you do have to make an 
incision from that standpoint it is invasive 
other experts fear a backlash against the traditional donation 
system at this time its not the way were accustomed to 
said howard nathan executive director of the delaware valley 
transplant program in philadelphia if a plan like that were 
implemented it would take some time to get the medical community 
and public used to that type of procedure 
anaise is prepared for resistance although he has permission 
from university hospital in stony brook to try the procedure 
provided there is family consent or a signed donor card he wants 
to familiarize his colleagues and the public with the idea before 
he proceeds 
the public may say this is horrible those kidneysnatchers i 
came to the emergency room for a checkup and ended up being a 
donor he said 
anaise emphasizes the procedure would not be implemented until 
patients are pronounced dead 
nothing will be done until the time that normally an orderly 
would have come to pick up this body and take it to the morgue 
he said 
anaise said at the transplant societys annual meeting that he 
would attach a catheter to patients without heartbeats for flushing 
preservatives into their kidneys and removing blood from the 
organs chilled solution then would be pumped from an ice bucket 
through two tubes inserted into the abdomen to keep the kidneys 
cold 
the only marks on the body would be a 2inch incision in the 
groin area from the catheter and two small stab wounds in the 
abdomen anaise said 
basically you have a nonmutilated body he said 
if relatives decide against donation they can take it the 
body and bury it and the mortician will tell you thank you you 
did basically what a mortician would have done anyhow 
</TEXT>
