<TEXT>
the foreign ministry is renewing efforts 
to persuade the us government to lift its ban on president kurt 
waldheim traveling to the united states a ministry official said 
friday 
the united states barred waldheim from the country on april 27 
1987 after the world jewish congress said it had evidence that 
implicated the former united nations secretary general in war 
crimes during world war ii 
the us justice department said in december 1987 that it had 
evidence of waldheims complicity while he served as a junior 
officer in the german army in yugoslavia in world war ii 
waldheim who was elected president in 1986 has denied all the 
charges 
members of austrias coalition government are divided over 
whether it should press the united states to lift the travel ban 
chancellor franz vranitzky visited the united states less than a 
month ago and saw no reason to raise the issue in a meeting with 
government officials said a spokesman on condition of anonymity 
but a foreign ministry official said there is a plan to hand 
president bush a letter through ambassador friedrich hoess in which 
the new administration is once more given the austrian viewpoint on 
this topic 
the ban was imposed during president reagans second term in 
office 
the foreign ministry official who spoke on condition of 
anonymity said the letter did not contain new arguments it was to 
be delivered in the next few days the official said 
vranitzky is chairman of the socialist party foreign minister 
alois mock until recently headed the conservative austrian peoples 
party 
an international commission of historians appointed by the 
austrian government issued a report in february 1988 that said 
waldheim was in close proximity to some war atrocities knew 
they were going on and made no attempt to stop them 
the us justice department has said its evidence shows 
waldheims complicity in the deportation of jews from greek islands 
to concentration or death camps the execution of allied prisoners 
and the execution of hostages and other civilians 
