who volunteered she said 
alireza jafarzadeh an organizer for the peoples mujahedeen 
said i know personally hundreds by name who have gone in the past 
year and definitely there are more than that 
the iranians said they were making their own arrangements to get 
visas to travel to iraq and declined to provide details 
spokesman for the peoples mujahedeen said the volunteers travel 
independently and join the resistance army when they arrive in iraq 
jafarzadeh said that is why there are no exact figures on the 
number of exiles who have left america 
the national liberation army has an estimated 15000 fighters 
jafarzadeh said when the iranians arrive in iraq they undego 
training for weeks or months depending on their skills and the 
tasks they will carry out they then are placed in various army 
units and the assignments are not based on what country they came 
from he said 
the national liberation army established in 1987 conducted an 
offensive last july called eternal light and claimed two 
iranian border cities were captured 
it said its fighters then withdrew and asserted that during the 
campaign they killed or wounded 55000 iranians and suffered only 
1000 casualties 
iran said it trounced the opposition army killing or capturing 
thousands irans ambassador to the united nations said iran 
sustained 40000 casualties 
londonbased amnesty international and a un human rights 
investigator said iran embarked on a wave of executions of 
political prisoners after that campaign with most of the victims 
being mujahedeen sympathizers 
the iraniraq ended last year with a ceasefire proposed in 
security council resolution 598 
