legislators can use to enhance the effectiveness of insurance 
regulation in their states 
pia national president david l ream said both consumers and 
insurance agents will benefit if minimum standards are implemented 
in all the states as a result consumers would be able to receive 
price comparison information more readily and agents would have 
greater assurance that the companies they place their customers 
business with are financially sound 
highlights of the proposal 
strengthen the size and quality of state regulatory agencies by 
allocating to their budgets at least 10 percent of the premium 
taxes insurers pay annually to the states most agencies now 
operate with much smaller budgets equivalent on average to 6 
percent of the premium taxes collected 
bar regulatory officials from entering the employment of 
insurance companies for one year after leaving their official 
positions 
draw up specified time periods in which claims should be paid 
and maintain and disclose complaint information by company and line 
of insurance 
conduct routine financial examinations of companies to make 
sure funds are available to pay claims 
maintain readily accessible price information on personal 
auto insurance so conumers can make onestop comparisons 
appoint independent consumer advocates or councils for advice 
on regulatory policies 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

