<TEXT>
eastern airlines said today it plans austerity 
measures that will include temporary changes in wages and 
benefits for its nonunion employees and reassignment of some 
management workers to permanently replace striking machinists 
the company declined to elaborate but did state that the changes 
were aimed at satisfying creditors of the strikebound airline 
indicating wage and benefit cuts were likely 
in a brief statement eastern said the changes were needed 
because of financial difficulties created by the 3monthold strike 
against the carrier and its bankruptcy proceeding 
the company scheduled an afternoon news conference in miami to 
outline what it called changes in wages vacation policies and 
other benefits areas 
eastern spokesman james ashlock in miami described the changes 
as austerity measures aimed at satisfying creditors as the airline 
moves ahead with its recently announced plan to reorganize as a 
smaller carrier 
because eastern aims to reduce its workforce to 17000 employees 
after having nearly 30000 before the strike middlemanagement 
positions were likely to be targeted ashlock said 
a lot of people will be offered other positions he said 
noting that many middlelevel management people have been 
performing new jobs to replace the striking union workers 
eastern currently has 4500 to 5000 nonunion employees most 
